% v2 conclusion draft. Leads with the architectural pivot and keeps
% v1's "within-system ablation" as supporting evidence.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

ET-MCP names a coordination primitive for multi-agent LLM systems:
typed events biased toward negative knowledge, task-scoped, addressed
through an MCP-conformant transport.  Two reader-side architectures
realize the primitive: a \emph{pull} interface that hands the agent
the decision to query, and an \emph{intercept} layer that relocates
the read to the framework.  Within-system evidence from the
TravelPlanner factorial isolates the pull channel as load-bearing
under constant payload; cross-protocol evidence on $\tau^2$-bench
retail at $n{=}30$ tasks shows the intercept layer outperforms both
pull and no-coordination on pass$^k$ (Cliff's $\delta=$TODO,
$p=$TODO Holm-corrected) while using TODO\% fewer input tokens
than no-coordination.  Pull is not better than no-coordination on
this benchmark---the architectural pivot is the v2 contribution.

We release the $\sim$300-line Anthropic-native $\tau^2$-bench harness
that made these measurements reproducible after the bundled
litellm-based pipeline could not.  Coordination primitives deserve
not only a first-class substrate in the MCP toolchain but also a
framework-side reader path; ET-MCP-intercept is a concrete proposal
for both.
